{"cursor":"7486","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Magnetostatics' is the study of magnetic fields in systems where the currents\nare steady (not changing with time). It is the magnetic analogue of\nelectrostatics, where the charges are stationary. The magnetization need not be\nstatic; the equations of magnetostatics can be used to predict fast magnetic\nswitching events that occur on time scales of nanoseconds or less. Magnetostatics is even a good approximation when the\ncurrents are not static — as long as the currents do not alternate\nrapidly. Magnetostatics is widely used in applications of micromagnetics such as\nmodels of magnetic recording devices.\n","linknr":290,"url":"Magnetostatics","recorded":1362485695,"links":39,"instances":["physics","electromagnetism"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Electric and magnetic fields in matter","Magnetostatics","Potential"],"headings":["Applications","Solving for the magnetic field","See also","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/VFPt_Solenoid_correct2.svg/190px-VFPt_Solenoid_correct2.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/1/0/210d7dc064d15959b1f8171b5057de56.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/d/8/dd89480478cc4d090d6705b85ef6e270.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/a/f/8af8616fb87d3450b3effc7f968e634a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/c/3/4c33ed996125b5b7a1385b5d301fa677.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/1/7/217d512cc66d5a36e037c7070b358ff9.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/d/b/5dbc98dcc983a70728bd082d1a47546e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/4/9/6497f1826708c6d15e6d0eefa940b182.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/d/6/0d61f8370cad1d412f80b84d143e1257.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/c/3/1c3a639eba17ccc632fdba79b07598ed.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/f/52f0da4247d02562c5aedb13d8ba4385.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/1/0/210d7dc064d15959b1f8171b5057de56.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/d/f/ddfa83a96d011492350d5e74526e3b09.png","//uploa